<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 22 日星期六 00:16:30 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Brazil Cracks Down on Gun Owners]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦发誓要扭转右翼前任领导下的枪支泛滥现象<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074310"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821835?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦自一月份上任以来已通过了多项措施来控制枪支所有权。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：marcelo camargo/讲义/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074310"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/samantha-pearson" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨曼莎·皮尔森 卢西亚娜</a></span>·马加拉斯</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 4:02 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>圣保罗——巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦周五通过了一项加强枪支管制的法令，这是继右翼前任雅伊尔·博尔索纳罗领导下的枪支<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-moves-to-take-back-guns-after-surge-in-purchases-87a06cdd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">购买激增</a>之后，他最近努力从拉丁美洲最大国家的街道上清除枪支。</p><p>达席尔瓦在总统府举行的仪式上签署了该法令，承诺“让国家恢复正常”，将巴西人可以购买的自卫枪支数量从四支减少到两支，每年的弹药津贴从200发子弹减少到50发，并禁止24小时射击俱乐部。</p><p>自达席尔瓦一月份上任以来，该法令还采取了一系列其他措施来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-new-president-reverses-his-predecessors-loosened-gun-laws-11672693693?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">控制枪支所有权</a>，其中包括在他就任总统几个小时后就通过的禁止携带已装弹武器的禁令。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>枪支管制在巴西已成为一个严重分歧的问题，该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/graphics/how-does-your-city-compare-to-latin-american-violence/?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">枪支犯罪猖獗</a>，截至 2017 年，该国的凶杀案数量比世界上任何地方都多，而且大多是使用枪支实施的。</p><p>虽然达席尔瓦的左翼工人党和许多犯罪专家认为，减少流通的枪支数量将减少枪支犯罪，但博尔索纳罗和右翼政治团体则认为，巴西人应该有权<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-has-an-idea-to-fix-rampant-gun-violence-more-guns-11546315200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保护自己</a>免受该国全副武装的犯罪分子的侵害。</p><p>达席尔瓦在周五的一次演讲中表示：“我们将继续努力解除巴西的武装——应该武装的是警察和武装部队。”他在演讲中还宣布了加强亚马逊地区贩毒路线沿线警务的措施。</p><p> “我们不能允许人们积累武器库，”他说。达席尔瓦说：“我们不能确定这些枪支只卖给正派和诚实的人，这些人只是想要一把枪来保护自己。”他补充说，他担心宽松的枪支法会让犯罪分子更容易武装自己。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821721?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">达席尔瓦的法令强制射击俱乐部在晚上 10 点关闭，而不是全天候营业。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马蒂亚斯·德拉克罗瓦/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据新法令，购买枪支用于狩猎的巴西人将可以拥有六支枪，而不是之前的 30 支。在博尔索纳罗的领导下，猎人的枪支销量猛增，引发了反枪支活动人士的批评，他们认为，在一个猎杀野猪以外的动物是非法的国家，向猎人提供这么多枪支毫无意义。</p><p>政府表示，以前将射击作为一项运动的巴西人每年最多可以购买 15 万发子弹，而现在在某些情况下只能购买到 4,000 发子弹。该法令还禁止使用某些枪支，例如 9 毫米手枪，并强制射击俱乐部在晚上 10 点关闭，而不是全天候营业。</p><p>在博尔索纳罗的领导下，枪支拥有者只要在前往射击俱乐部的途中就可以携带已装弹的枪支。巴西司法部长弗拉维奥·迪诺表示，他怀疑一些俱乐部继续营业只是为了给会员提供合法借口，让他们可以在白天或晚上随时携带上膛的武器。</p><p> “你会在凌晨两点用上了膛的武器逮捕一个人，他会说他正在去射击俱乐部的路上，”迪诺周五在仪式结束后接受电视采访时说。</p><p>但巴西的许多枪支拥有者表示，政府的镇压是不公平的。</p><p> “这对这项运动来说很糟糕，”戈亚斯州中部一家枪支配件商店的店主古斯塔沃·马里亚诺说。 “在靶场一天，一个人可以发射一千发子弹，这些规则使它不可行。”</p><p>枪支俱乐部老板古斯塔沃·帕齐尼表示，如果巴西人无法训练如何正确射击，那么他们最终将受到犯罪分子的摆布。 “没有射击俱乐部，就没有运动……而犯罪分子却仍然装备精良。”</p><p>写信给 Samantha Pearson（ <a href="mailto:samantha.pearson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">samantha.pearson@wsj.com）</a>和 Luciana Magalhaes（ <a href="mailto:luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3<author><![CDATA[Samantha Pearson]]></author><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>枪支控制</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>射击</category><category>社会问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>枪支控制</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>射击</category><category>社会问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Arrests Militant Right-Wing Critic Igor Girkin in Widening Crackdown]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>克里姆林宫在多年镇压倾向西方的领导人后向民族主义者和军事领导人施加压力<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073978"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821729?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊戈尔·吉尔金周五在莫斯科被拘留，并被指控犯有极端主义罪。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alexander zemlianichenko/新闻池</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073978"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alan-cullison" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾伦·卡里森</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/thomas-grove" itemprop="url" rel="author">托马斯·格罗夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 2:34 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>俄罗斯调查人员周五逮捕了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>总统的一位著名右翼批评者，这是对公开宣称的俄罗斯爱国者的更广泛镇压，这些爱国者攻击普京未能以足够的力度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在乌克兰进行战争</a>。</p><p>伊戈尔·吉尔金 (Igor Girkin) 是一位强烈的民族主义人物，也是俄罗斯支持的乌克兰东部武装分子的前领导人，据他的妻子称，他被拘留在莫斯科的公寓中，并被指控犯有极端主义罪，她在这位前军官受欢迎的 Telegram 频道上宣布了对他的拘留。国营塔斯社证实了他的被捕。</p><p>普京多年来一直镇压左翼和西倾反对者，以维护其23年的统治，但在上个月末准军事领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任领导的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">兵变之后</a>，他也开始镇压右翼批评者，这些批评者因他入侵乌克兰而变得更加大胆。</p><p>其中化名斯特雷科夫在乌克兰东部写作和活动的吉尔金因对普京的严厉批评而脱颖而出，但他最新的评论似乎越界了。</p><p>最近，他在 Telegram 频道上发帖称普京是一个“无足轻重的人”，他设法“把灰尘扔到俄罗斯人民的眼睛里”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>吉尔金显然是指明年的俄罗斯总统选举，届时预计普京将寻求连任六年，吉尔金写道，“这个国家将无法在这种懦弱的平庸政权的统治下再存活六年。”</p><p>吉尔金的被捕立即激怒了民族主义圈子，他们赞扬了他针对普京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-u-k-spy-chief-says-894d62c2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">笨手笨脚地入侵</a>乌克兰的愤怒信件。</p><p>吉尔金的一名同胞试图在他被拘留的法庭外举行抗议。与吉尔金一起创立民族主义愤怒爱国者俱乐部（KRP）的帕维尔·古巴列夫（Pavel Gubarev）表示，吉尔金“从一开始就正确地批评了国防部的行动”。法院下令将 Girkin 关押至 9 月 18 日举行的下一次听证会。</p><p>民族主义活动家格奥尔基·费奥多罗夫称吉尔金被捕是更广泛镇压的先兆。</p><p>他写道：“这是一个非常坏的消息，意味着镇压不仅针对KRP成员，而且针对整个活跃的爱国社区，这显然对最高权力来说已经变得危险。” “我们必须团结起来支持斯特列科夫，因为这只是开始。”</p><p>自从6月24日普里戈任在莫斯科发生兵变和游行失败后，俄罗斯当局开始在军队中清洗可能同情这位准军事领导人及其私人军事连的军官。</p><p>虽然吉尔金对国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古和总参谋长瓦列里·格拉西莫夫将军的批评与普里戈任的批评相呼应，但他的拘留是一系列与叛变无关的现任和退休军官中最新的一个，这表明克里姆林宫正在对那些涉嫌分裂忠诚的人采取更广泛的措施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月兵变后，俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京开始镇压右翼批评者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：SPUTNIK/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>本月早些时候，乌克兰南部的一名俄罗斯高级指挥官因批评军方领导层对战争的管理而被免职。在泄露的录音带中，伊万·波波夫少将表示，他因向军事领导人说实话而被免职，其中包括直接控制俄罗斯乌克兰战争的格拉西莫夫。</p><p>本周早些时候，俄罗斯当局还对退役上校提出指控。</p>吉尔金在本周早些时候的 Telegram 帖子中写道，前军事情报官员弗拉基米尔·克瓦奇科夫 (Vladimir Kvachkov) 曾因 2009 年企图武装叛乱的指控而入狱。10 年后他被释放，但现在面临着抹黑军队的新指控。<p></p><p> 2014年普京占领克里米亚后，吉尔金成为俄罗斯极端民族主义者和民族统一主义者的象征，当时吉尔金领导一群俄罗斯支持的民兵占领了乌克兰城市斯拉维扬斯克。他很快就以残酷的手段和即决处决而闻名。</p><p>他升任​​为俄罗斯支持的顿涅茨克分裂主义小国的假定国防部长，叛军击落马来西亚航空公司一架民用航班、机上 298 名乘客和机组人员全部遇难时，他就担任了这个职务。去年，吉尔金和另外两名武装分子被荷兰法院判定犯有大规模谋杀罪。他否认对此负有责任。</p><p>逃往俄罗斯后，吉尔金一直指责克里姆林宫未能以足够的力度进行对乌克兰的战争，包括他支持的去年的入侵。</p><p>写信给 Alan Cullison <a href="mailto:alan.cullison@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(alan.cullison@wsj.com)</a>和 Thomas Grove ( <a href="mailto:thomas.grove@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">thomas.grove@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308<author><![CDATA[Alan CullisonThomas Grove]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>伊戈尔·吉尔金</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. to Send More Warships, Marines to Middle East Amid Rising Tensions With Iran]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>过去三个月，华盛顿向该地区派遣了部队，阻止伊朗军队针对商船<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072734"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="688" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821405?width=860&amp;height=688" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">监控视频拍摄的图像显示，上个月，三艘伊朗船只靠近霍尔木兹海峡的一艘商船。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国海军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072734"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dion-nissenbaum" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪昂·尼森鲍姆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日中午 12:22（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国军方表示，正在向中东派遣更多军舰和海军陆战队员，以阻止伊朗在该地区扣押更多船只。</p><p>五角大楼周四晚间表示，在美国海军挫败了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-tried-to-seize-two-oil-tankers-near-strait-of-hormuz-u-s-navy-says-4be301e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">伊朗本月早些时候在阿曼湾国际水域扣押两艘油轮的企图</a>后，国防部长劳埃德·奥斯汀下令向该地区增派新部队。一名美国军方官员表示，此举并不是针对特定的新威胁，而是针对伊朗的行动。</p><p>中东盟友一直敦促美国采取更多措施对抗伊朗，伊朗在今年春天的一周内扣押了两艘油轮，其中一艘将科威特原油运往休斯敦，供<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CVX" class="">雪佛龙</a>公司使用<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-pressured-to-secure-persian-gulf-after-iran-seizes-tankers-7bab70cb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">阿拉伯联合酋长国对美国对今年早些时候伊朗扣押油轮事件缺乏回应表示特别失望</a>，并呼吁五角大楼向波斯湾派遣更多部队。</p><p>过去三个月，美国向中东派遣了一系列部队，阻止伊朗军队干扰通过该地区的商船。</p><p> 4月初，在伊朗扣押两艘油轮之前，美国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sends-submarine-to-middle-east-in-show-of-force-441dbb42?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">派出一艘导弹潜艇</a>进入红海。扣押事件发生后，美国向该地区派遣了一艘导弹驱逐舰，并使用侦察机密切监视阿曼湾一艘油轮周围的伊朗海军活动。</p><p>即使有新的动向，美国在中东的军事存在仍将远远小于伊拉克和阿富汗战争期间部署的兵力，因为五角大楼近年来一直寻求将战略重点转向中国和俄罗斯。但伊朗的行动，包括最近对波斯湾航运的威胁，促使五角大楼将部队转移回中东。</p><p>此外，俄罗斯喷气式战斗机加大了对叙利亚上空美国飞机的骚扰力度，美国官员表示，这似乎是莫斯科向美国施压，迫使其从该地区撤军。美国官员表示，伊朗人也有同样的目标。</p><p>负责监督美国在叙利亚以及中东和东南亚其他 20 个国家上空的军事行动的空军中将亚历克苏斯·格林克维奇 (Alexus Grynkewich) 上个月表示，“伊朗人当然希望联军撤离叙利亚，这样他们就可以有行动自由，让伊朗结盟团体为了自己的目的而在叙利亚各地运送先进的常规武器和致命能力。”</p><p>迄今为止，美国威慑伊朗的努力收效有限。</p><p>本月早些时候，美国海军挫败了伊朗军队两次分别扣押两艘商业油轮的企图。海军表示，第二天，伊朗军队确实扣押了第三艘涉嫌走私石油的商船。对于这种情况，美国海军表示没有干预。</p><p>美国现在正在采取更多措施来对抗伊朗。本周早些时候， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-deploys-advanced-f-35-jets-destroyer-to-middle-east-to-brush-back-iranian-forces-7d9a92cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">五角大楼表示将向该地区派遣最先进的喷气式战斗机</a>——F-35。现在，五角大楼正在派遣一个海军陆战队两栖战备小组和海军陆战队远征部队，其中至少有两艘舰艇和最多 2,500 名海军陆战队员。</p><p>美国中央司令部司令、陆军上将埃里克·库里拉表示，新部队将有助于“保障国际商业的自由流动……维护基于规则的国际秩序，并阻止伊朗在该地区破坏稳定的活动。”</p><p>美国军方表示，过去两年，伊朗已针对该地区近20艘商船进行攻击。</p><p>美国对抗伊朗的努力超出了波斯湾。今年三月，五角大楼<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-strikes-iranian-backed-group-in-syria-after-drone-attack-kills-one-american-and-wounds-six-9f3dafe6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">针对叙利亚境内伊朗支持的武装分子进行了空袭</a>，以应对无人机袭击叙利亚境内美国基地并造成一名美国承包商死亡的事件。</p><p>美国官员表示，美国的袭击迫使伊朗缩减了针对该地区美军的企图。但伊朗反而加大了针对波斯湾商船的攻击力度，全球超过三分之一的海运原油都在此过境。</p><p>写信给迪昂·尼森鲍姆 (Dion Nissenbaum)： <a href="mailto:dion.nissenbaum@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dion.nissenbaum@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 16:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048<author><![CDATA[Dion Nissenbaum]]></author><category>活力</category><category>军用船只</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>工业品</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>活力</category><category>军用船只</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>国防装备</category><category>产品</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>工业品</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Sergey Brin Is Back in the Trenches at Google]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>联合创始人正在与科技巨头总部的人工智能研究人员一起工作，协助建立强大的 Gemini 系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="577" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821144?width=860&amp;height=577" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林长期以来对人工智能技术很感兴趣，他定期与参与人工智能研究的谷歌员工会面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JUNG YEON-JE/​​法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈尔斯·克鲁帕</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 10:10（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林重返工作岗位。</p><p>近几个月来，这位亿万富翁每周都会访问这家科技巨头位于加州山景城的办公室，通常每周三到四天，与研究人员一起努力开发该公司的下一个大型人工智能系统。</p><p>知情人士称，布林去年年底参加了谷歌办公室有关人工智能的会议，但他参与的频率和强度有所增加。他的新立场与他在 2019 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sundar-pichai-to-replace-larry-page-as-ceo-of-alphabet-11575409229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞去</a>母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabet</a>高管职务后采取的相对不干涉的态度发生了显着变化。</p><p>他与一组研究人员密切合作，构建了谷歌期待已久的人工智能模型 Gemini。他们讨论了诸如“损失曲线”之类的技术问题，这是一种衡量人工智能程序随时间推移表现的方法，布林还每周与谷歌员工就新的人工智能研究进行讨论。知情人士称，他还干预人事事务，例如聘用受欢迎的研究人员。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，布林在谷歌的影响力增加反映了人工智能的关键时刻以及他对这项技术的长期兴趣。谷歌是该技术的先驱，但在将其转化为新产品方面比竞争对手慢。</p><p>随着 Meta Platforms 等公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近推出的新产品</a>，人工智能研究领域的竞争正在加剧。谷歌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-tries-to-catch-up-to-rivals-like-openai-as-they-release-viral-apps-11674828418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了产品开发速度，</a>以应对去年发布的 ChatGPT，这是一款由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的研究公司 OpenAI 开发的人工智能聊天机器人，可以流畅地响应一系列书面查询。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820793?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌创始人谢尔盖·布林和拉里·佩奇从斯坦福大学博士生起就一直在一起工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·内格尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Gemini 是 Google 尝试构建的<a href="https://blog.google/technology/ai/google-palm-2-ai-large-language-model/" target="_blank" class="icon none">通用人工智能</a>程序，可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/openai-rolls-out-updated-version-of-viral-chatbot-chatgpt-f03fea27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 的 GPT-4 模型</a>相媲美，该模型为 ChatGPT 的付费版本提供支持。据知情人士透露，负责该项目的谷歌高管德米斯·哈萨比斯 (Demis Hassabis) 在最近的一次全公司会议上告诉员工，该项目将于今年晚些时候推出。</p><p> 49 岁的布林于 1998 年与拉里·佩奇 (Larry Page) 一起创立了谷歌，他们在斯坦福大学攻读博士时共同进行了网络搜索研究。</p><p>虽然布林近年来偶尔出现在谷歌总部，但他的注意力主要集中在飞艇和新形式的灾难援助等外部利益上，以及捐赠部分巨额财富的努力。根据 S&amp;P Capital IQ 的数据，他是 Alphabet 的第二大个人股东，仅次于 Page，所持股份价值接近 900 亿美元。</p><p>自从谷歌在 5 月份的年度开发者大会上宣布一系列人工智能产品以来，Alphabet 的股价已经上涨了 10% 以上，其中包括新版本的核心搜索引擎，该引擎提供了冗长的摘要并邀请后续问题。这一涨幅与竞争对手微软的股价和更广泛的纳斯达克综合指数大致一致。</p><p>知情人士称，布林大部分时间都在新建的查尔斯顿东大楼里与山景城的人工智能研究人员坐在一起，该大楼距离谷歌公司园区原来的中心仅几步之遥。谷歌和 Alphabet 的首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊 (Sundar Pichai) 也在大楼内设有办公室。</p><p>四年前，当创始人辞去日常职务并将皮查伊提拔为 Alphabet 首席执行官时，他们表示将定期与他交谈并提供“建议和爱，但不会每天唠叨”。他们仍然控制着 Alphabet 的多数投票权，并与皮查伊一起担任执行董事会委员会成员。</p><p>据一位了解皮查伊想法的人士透露，皮查伊对布林的参与感到兴奋，并鼓励他做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="475" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820792?width=700&amp;height=475" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2012 年，谢尔盖·布林 (Sergey Brin) 与一辆自动驾驶汽车在谷歌山景城总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>谷歌在人工智能领域处于领先地位，于 2011 年成立了一个名为 Brain 的研究部门，研究如何使用称为深度学习的计算技术来构建广泛有用的人工智能程序。</p><p> Pichai 今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabets-google-combines-ai-research-units-brain-and-deepmind-620f4f7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将 Brain 团队与 DeepMind 合并</a>，DeepMind 是一家人工智能研究公司，此前在 Alphabet 旗下独立运营。这次改组将 DeepMind 联合创始人哈萨比斯提升为合并后的 Google DeepMind 集团的首席执行官。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，一些研究人员接受了布林的参与，认为这是对他们工作的认可，也是人工智能团队在过渡时期的有益干预。哈萨比斯和许多 Google DeepMind 高管在伦敦工作，使该办公室成为新设置中事实上的权力中心。</p><p>自 11 月份 ChatGPT 发布以来，布林的参与度不断增加。据《纽约时报》早些时候报道的知情人士透露，谷歌的联合创始人参加了会议，审查谷歌正在为 5 月份的开发者大会准备的人工智能产品。</p><p>此后，布林一直在谷歌总部保持着强大的影响力，经常出席研究聚会和公司庆祝活动。谷歌表示，除了联合创始人和董事会成员之外，布林在公司没有正式的新角色。布林的发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>佩奇在管理谷歌期间有时是一个隐居的人物，而布林却培养了一个更平易近人的形象，穿着溜冰鞋穿越总部，在公司的各个项目之间穿梭。</p><p>据与布林有过互动的人士透露，自从去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能热潮</a>以来，布林就参加了该公司的发布会，该公司推广了图像生成程序 Stable Diffusion，并且偶尔也会参加在加利福尼亚州希尔斯伯勒一座价值 6800 万美元的豪宅（即 AGI House）举行的活动。 AGI 代表通用人工智能，即计算机程序有一天可以与人类推理相匹配。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820384?width=700&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，谷歌首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊、谢尔盖·布林、卢森堡首相泽维尔·贝特尔和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢森堡国务部</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年3月，在<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/xavier-bettel_thanks-to-sundar-pichai-and-kent-walker-activity-7041634974231351296-hDnQ/" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢森堡首相访问期间，布林被拍到与皮查伊和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克在谷歌总部合影</a>，布林身着灰色运动裤和黑色长袖衬衫。其他与会者都穿着西装。</p><p>布林与 Gemini 的合作是谷歌长期努力构建人工智能系统的又一成果，这些系统可以展现出类人的能力，并更无缝地满足该公司数十亿用户的需求。</p><p>布林在 2017 年 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffvu6Mr1SVc&amp;t=92s" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界经济论坛上接受采访</a>时表示，起初，布林忽视了 Brain 团队的工作，并对他们能否破解人工智能表示怀疑，尽管该团队始于他领导的 Google X 部门。</p><p> “说实话，我根本没有注意它，”布林说。他说，几年后，Brain 的研究被用于谷歌许多最大的产品，颠覆了他之前的假设。</p><p>布林在一定程度上关注了人事问题，随着人工智能研究人员的人才争夺战加剧，这对谷歌和其他大型科技公司来说是一个困难的领域。 2017 年，谷歌发表了一篇具有里程碑意义的论文，该论文被认为引发了最新一波人工智能发展浪潮，该论文的多位作者已离开该公司，为竞争对手的初创公司筹集数亿美元资金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>谢尔盖·布林会让谷歌在人工智能领域更具竞争力吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，尽管布林是世界上最受尊敬的计算机科学家之一，但他需要赶上人工智能的最新发展，并且没有为编码项目做出重大贡献。</p><p>布林在 2018 年发布的上一封股东信中宣传了人工智能的可能性，他写道，“计算解决重要问题的力量和潜力从未如此强大。”</p><p> “人工智能的新春天是我一生中计算领域最重大的发展，”他写道。</p><p>写信给 Miles Kruppa ( <a href="mailto:miles.kruppa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">miles.kruppa@wsj.com)</a>和 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e<author><![CDATA[Miles KruppaDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>谢尔盖·布林</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Soldier’s Crossing Into North Korea Points to Security Gaps]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>特拉维斯·金本应登上飞往德克萨斯州的航班，然后才出现在非军事区的一个旅游景点<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073010"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821490?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国士兵特拉维斯·金在韩国面临袭击指控。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：社交媒体/VIA REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073010"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">达斯尔·尹</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 9:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——特拉维斯·金原定于周一乘坐美国航空的航班从韩国起飞。他从来没有成功过。</p><p>相反，在德克萨斯州面临潜在军事纪律处分的美国士兵一天后最终<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">越境进入朝鲜</a>，一系列事件引发了人们对非军事区旅游景点的安全措施以及美军对金计划离开的处理的质疑。</p><p>朝鲜尚未回应美国就金的地位与该政权接触的努力。金是一名 23 岁的陆军二等兵。 “坦率地说，我担心他，”陆军部长克里斯汀·沃穆斯周四在阿斯彭举行的一次会议上表示。</p><p>据美国和机场官员称，金在韩国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面临袭击指控</a>，周一由美国军人护送到仁川机场，登上美国航空飞往德克萨斯州的航班。他将在德克萨斯州受到军官的会面，并面临纪律处分和可能的开除。</p><p>据机场官员称，在通过机场的安全检查站后，金告诉航空公司工作人员他找不到自己的护照。随后他被护送至出发侧。从那里，他似乎趁机溜出了机场。</p><p>第二天，他出现在联合安全区的参观中，该区域位于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officer-on-a-pink-phone-dials-down-north-korea-tensions-11558287392?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">非军事区内</a>，是游客可以到达的距离朝鲜最近的区域。</p><p>韩国国家安全委员会前官员千成勋 (Cheon Seong-whun) 表示：“美国军方将不得不重新评估安全措施，特别是在管理在海外面临指控的士兵方面。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D69C17D9-A239-4491-A945-60AAB8A04205&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">白宫新闻秘书表示，周二，一名美国陆军一等兵特拉维斯·金 (Travis King) 士兵在参观联合安全区时越过军事分界线，随后美国正在​​与朝鲜当局合作。照片：安东尼·华莱士/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>据一位知情人士透露，金被护送至海关，但飞机上没有美国军人陪同，因为他在韩国拘留所服刑后不再​​被视为罪犯。驻韩美军发言人没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>去年，金在韩国的两起不同事件中面临袭击指控，之后被拘留了近 50 天。在十月的第二起事件中，据称他踢坏了一辆警车。 2月份，他因该事件被罚款4,000美元。</p><p>沃穆斯说：“他在韩国袭击了一个人，并被韩国政府拘留，他将返回美国并在军队中承担后果。” “我确信他正在努力解决这个问题。”</p><p>金是在参观联合安全区（也称为板门店）时穿越的，该地区一直是军事谈判、和平谈判和囚犯交换的场所。联合安全区位于非军事区内，沿线 150 英里由铁丝网和地雷把守。</p><p>在联合安全区，分隔朝鲜两国的唯一障碍是一条很容易被踩过去的短砖线。前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>于 2019 年这样做，成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-says-north-koreas-kim-wants-to-meet-11561862697?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第一位进入朝鲜的在任总统</a>，当时他在那里会见了朝鲜领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820431?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据路透社报道，身穿黑色衬衫、头戴帽子的特拉维斯·金 (Travis King) 是周二访问韩国非军事区的游客之一，随后他穿越了边境。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：莎拉·莱斯利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管保安人员驻扎在联合安全区的韩国一侧，但他们被禁止越过界限进入朝鲜追捕某人。 2017年，一名朝鲜士兵冲过边境，其他朝鲜士兵向他开枪。但根据朝韩军事协议，自 2018 年以来，共同安全区的所有警卫都没有携带武器。</p><p>首尔官员表示，金可能不得不提前计划对联合安全区的访问。 7月10日，他被从拘留所释放。一周后，他被护送至仁川机场。旅游机构通常在旅行前一周接受参观联合安全区的申请，以获得负责监督联合安全区的美国领导的联合国司令部的许可。</p><p> King 参加了由韩国 HanaTour ITC 公司运营的非军事区全日游。该旅游团专门为美国军人提供联合安全区旅游，但金为普通游客单独预订了旅游。 HanaTour ITC 拒绝就所涉及的安全程序或金如何逃往朝鲜发表评论。</p><p>要进入非军事区，韩国或美国士兵通常会根据导游提交的名单上的姓名验证身份。一名韩国官员表示，尽管美军在联合安全区巡视，但仍不知道他的行踪，这对军方来说是“巨大的尴尬”。</p><p>在平壤和华盛顿之间紧张局势加剧之际，金现在掌握在朝鲜手中。朝鲜拒绝与美国进行正式会谈，并就其与首尔的军事演习以及部署韩国核资产对华盛顿进行了猛烈抨击。本周，一艘能够发射核弹头的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国潜艇</a>四十年来首次抵达韩国港口。</p><p>前韩国国家安全委员会官员千说，朝鲜可能需要一些时间来调查金越境的动机以及他是否可以成为该政权有用的宣传资产。</p><p>美国官员表示，他们正试图通过多种渠道与朝鲜建立联系，其中包括设有与朝鲜相连的热线的联合国司令部，以及为在朝鲜的美国公民提供领事服务的瑞典。</p><p> “我们尚未成功与朝鲜取得联系，”沃穆斯说。 “我们想让他回到美国。我担心他们会如何对待他。”</p><p> —<em>道格·卡梅伦对本文做出了贡献。</em></p><p>写信给 Dasl Yoon，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 13:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733<author><![CDATA[Dasl Yoon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How a Tiny Archipelago Gave Russia a Foothold in the Atlantic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>长期捕鱼协议对法罗群岛的经济至关重要，但它也让俄罗斯船只能够进入北大西洋<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072705"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821413?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">法罗群岛的克里斯蒂安港。渔业是其支柱产业之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社，盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072705"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">苏尼·恩格尔·拉斯穆森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 8:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管自俄罗斯入侵乌克兰以来，欧洲一直在努力缩小安全漏洞，但北大西洋的一个小岛群为俄罗斯船只在其水域和港口捕鱼和停靠提供了漏洞，其中包括被指控从事间谍活动和破坏活动的船只。</p><p> Western nations are growing increasingly wary of what&#39;s going on in and around the Faroe Islands, a self-governing territory under the Kingdom of Denmark which has a longstanding fishing agreement with Moscow. The agreement lets Russian vessels call at Faroese ports, circumventing a ban from European Union ports.</p><p> It also gives Russian vessels fishing rights in waters shared between the Faroes and the UK, prompting the British government to push the Faroese to suspend it—something the islands&#39; leaders haven&#39;t yet agreed to do.</p><p> The dispute illustrates how Europe has sharpened its focus on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-submarines-test-nato-in-icy-north-atlantic-11593682201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">waterways in the North Sea and the North Atlantic</a> , as it enters a new era of great-power conflict with Russia after its invasion of Ukraine.</p><p> The Faroese-UK special area falls within a strategic transit route between Greenland, Iceland and the UK, known as the GIUK Gap, which since the Cold War has been a key access point for military operations in the North Atlantic. As countries have become more dependent on offshore energy facilities and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/wsj-the-future-of-everything/melting-ice-undersea-cables-how-the-arctic-is-getting-fast-internet/2a204ef7-e522-45cb-946c-44fc1e4600d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">undersea fiber cables</a> that enable internet access and financial transactions, the gap&#39;s importance has grown.</p><p> “Seabed critical infrastructure and energy infrastructure have been targeted and will be targeted in the future. It is an awareness that the US and Europe have been waking up to in the last year,” said Rebecca Pincus, director of the Polar Institute at the Wilson Center in Washington, DC </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821416?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A fishing boat on the quayside in Grimsby, England. The UK and the Faroe Islands share some fishing waters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: oli scarff/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Following criticism from the British, the Faroe Islands last week implemented new restrictions meaning that only 31 Russian vessels named in their bilateral agreement can access its ports. Previously, other Russian fishing vessels not named in the agreement could legally transship cargo or undergo repairs in Faroese harbors. Faroese Foreign Minister Høgni Hoydal said in an interview that the new step will decrease the number of Russian vessels by about 60%.</p><p> However, the named Russian ships will still be able to fish in the so-called special zone that the Faroes share with the UK, where British authorities aren&#39;t allowed to inspect them, according to a 1999 agreement with Denmark.</p><p> Mark Spencer, the British minister for food, farming and fisheries, told his Faroese counterpart Dennis Holm in January that “the decision to renew your deal with Russia impacts upon our bilateral relationship,” and expressed “grave concern that this situation may arise again during 2023,” according to a letter obtained by the Wall Street Journal through a freedom of information request.</p><p> A UK government spokesperson said London will continue to seek a ban on Russian vessels fishing in the UK-Faroes special area.</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whos-killing-off-residents-of-this-island-nation-crime-writers-1524243819?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wind-lashed Faroes</a> , with a population of 54,000 people, 70,000 sheep and around a half-a-million breeding pairs of puffins, have jurisdiction over their own trade policy and aren&#39;t a member of the EU, but their foreign and security policy is determined in Denmark. The Faroese-Russian fishing agreement, which dates back to 1977, allows the Faroese to fish primarily for cod in the Barents Sea and Russians to fish for herring and mackerel in Faroese waters. Fish constitutes about <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/faeroe-islands-boom-by-selling-salmon-to-russia-1424483776" target="_blank" class="icon none">90% of Faroese exports</a> . Danish politicians have said the agreement makes the Faroes, and by extension Denmark, vulnerable to Russian espionage and creates a rift with the EU. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821415?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mark Spencer said the British government is concerned about the Faroe Islands&#39; deal with Russia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Justin Ng/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warned-ukraine-not-to-attack-nord-stream-7777939b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sabotage last year of the Nord Stream pipeline</a> in the Baltic Sea showed the vulnerability of underwater infrastructure and the difficulty in identifying culprits. For instance, 77% of the UK&#39;s gas is imported from Norway through pipelines under the North Sea.</p><p> “Russia has invested a lot into being able to threaten these areas and carry out clandestine undersea activities,” said Nick Childs, senior fellow for naval forces and maritime security at the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London. “It is very much back in vogue again.”</p><p> Recent incidents have stoked anxiety in European capitals about the Russian presence in the Faroes.</p><p> Last year, after 2.6 miles of an undersea fiber-optic cable connecting a Norwegian satellite station with the mainland was cut and vanished without a trace, marine tracking data showed a Russian fishing trawler had crisscrossed over the cable more than 140 times in the days before it was severed, prompting suspicions of sabotage. The trawler&#39;s movements were first reported by Norwegian media outlets.</p><p> Following the incident, the trawler, Melkart-5, docked in the Faroes until May this year. Andrey Roman, deputy director of Murman SeaFood, which owns Melkart-5, denied allegations that the vessel had been involved in sabotage.</p><p> “Our company is a completely commercial company,” Roman said. “Our vessels are subject to control in Norwegian ports and on the high seas by the Norwegian authorities.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In November last year, Norwegian police in the northern port of Kirkenes searched two Russian fishing trawlers, Lira and Ester, which had arrived there straight from the Faroes, and found Soviet-era military radio equipment behind locked doors. The chief of Norwegian intelligence in the region told national media at the time that he suspected the vessels could be involved in espionage.</p><p> The two vessels currently have their transponders turned off, but have docked in the Faroes more than 200 times since 2015, according to marine trafficking data. They are both among the 31 vessels allowed to call at Faroese ports, according to a list provided by the Faroe Islands Fisheries Inspection.</p><p> A spokesperson for the Norwegian Police Security Service declined to comment on the allegations against the three Russian vessels, but said Norway was a target for Russian intelligence services, and that “it is obviously possible that ships, including civilian ones, can be used by Russian authorities as platforms to collect information as part of their activities.”</p><p> Hoydal, the Faroese foreign minister, said Faroese authorities had not detected any malign activity from Russian vessels in their waters. He also pointed out that the islands&#39; trade with Russia doesn&#39;t violate EU <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-shadow-of-sanctions-russia-courts-friends-boasts-resilience-at-flagship-economic-forum-d299b6bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sanctions against Moscow</a> , which exclude food items—although no EU nations currently trade fish with Russia.</p><p> “Since the beginning of Russia&#39;s war in Ukraine, we have introduced the same sanctions as the EU,” Hoydal said. “But we honor our agreements.”</p><p> A Faroese lawmaker in Copenhagen, Sjurdur Skaale, said the EU should remove tariffs on Faroese exports of processed seafood products to help the islands reduce their trade with Russia and suspend the agreement.</p><p> The Faroese earned privileged access to the Russian market in 2014, following the invasion of Crimea, when the islands chose not to follow EU sanctions on Russia. However, Iceland—another small territory depending on the seafood business—followed the EU&#39;s lead and was targeted by Russian counter sanctions. The following year, Iceland&#39;s economy contracted by about 1%.</p><p> “The stakes are high for smaller countries and territories,” Pincus said.</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 12:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>Agriculture</category><category> Fishing</category><category> Port/Harbor Operations</category><category> Water Transport/Shipping</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>International Sanctions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>间谍</category><category>Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>trade</category><category> external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>international sanctions</category><category>政治</category><category>间谍</category><category>trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>agriculture</category><category> fishing</category><category> port</category><category> harbor operations</category><category> water transport</category><category> shipping</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing Rushes to Shore Up Battered Private Economy. Skepticism Abounds.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> China vows to promote a private sector wobbly from years of regulatory crackdowns and pandemic controls, but investors aren&#39;t convinced <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072909"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821472?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A job fair in Chongqing. China&#39;s efforts to rekindle the private sector risks exacerbating youth unemployment</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stella Yifan Xie</a></span> in Hong Kong and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/raffaele-huang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Raffaele Huang</a></span> in Singapore</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 8:32 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> China&#39;s leadership is lavishing the country&#39;s beleaguered private sector with a sweeping show of support as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a nascent economic recovery falters</a> .</p><p> But grand declarations and rhetoric alone won&#39;t suffice, say economists and investors. Sluggish domestic demand and a widely held view that Beijing still favors its state-owned enterprises mean that sentiment among the private business owners—a group that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/china-xi-jinping-communist-party-congress/card/in-china-the-state-sector-is-in-private-sector-stutters-jyOYiDqUFiSBISBHVyyS?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">accounts for most of the economy&#39;s dynamism</a> and hiring—isn&#39;t likely to turn around, at least not in the near term.</p><p> In a high-profile pronouncement this week, China&#39;s Communist Party and the country&#39;s cabinet jointly unveiled a list of more than 30 guidelines vowing to make the private sector “bigger, better and stronger.” Authorities said the measures would level the playing field between privately-run and state-owned enterprises, promising to break down market barriers, expand financing for privately held companies and engage them in future policy consultations.</p><p> Beijing&#39;s outreach to the private sector—a segment that contributes about 60% of China&#39;s total output and 80% of urban employment—comes as growth in the world&#39;s second-largest economy is decelerating on multiple fronts. It also marks a reprieve from the previous three years, in which Chinese officials decimated industries including after-school education and property with a series of regulatory crackdowns and strict limits. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821477?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A truck production line in Xian. China&#39;s leadership has rolled out incentives to boost vehicle sales.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: FLORENCE LO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The measures, unveiled on Wednesday, drew public praise from several prominent entrepreneurs such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">Tencent Holdings</a> &#39; low-profile co-founder Pony Ma. The videogame and social media titan and other major internet companies have seen their business and profits pummeled by Beijing&#39;s sudden changes in regulation in the last two years.</p><p> Over the past few weeks, Chinese officials have showered investors and the business community with attention and public promises to buttress the sector. China&#39;s Premier Li Qiang met with executives from the country&#39;s biggest tech companies including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BABA" class="company-name">Alibaba Group Holding</a> and TikTok parent ByteDance, encouraging them to support the economy through innovation.</p><p> Officials also met local business leaders in the manufacturing and consumption sectors to survey the difficulties they face, and held meetings to reassure business associations from the US, Europe and Japan that the country remains open for foreign investment. They also rolled out incentives to boost vehicle sales.</p><p> Such support comes after China&#39;s internet companies lost over $1 trillion in market value since late 2020, when authorities scrapped fintech giant Ant Group&#39;s blockbuster initial public offering, kicking off a series of regulatory crackdowns. Government raids on global consultancies including Bain &amp; Co. this year, as well as an expanded version of anti-espionage law have also dampened animal spirits in the business community.</p><p> Despite this, economists and private entrepreneurs interviewed by The Wall Street Journal say that three years of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-covid-dropped-restrictions-reopen-xi-11673534796?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strict control of Covid-19</a> and concurrent regulatory campaigns have taken its toll. The recent purges in China&#39;s internet and private tutoring industry have left entrepreneurs wary of unexpectedly falling afoul of the Communist Party&#39;s social goals, said George Magnus, research associate at Oxford University and former chief economist at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBS" class="">UBS</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p></p><p> “The overall attitude toward the private sector is still one where they are subordinate to the interest of the state,” he said.</p><p> Much of the caution among private business and investors also reflects long-term economic headwinds such as the country&#39;s shrinking population as well as elevated local government and household debt. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821478?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A construction site in Zhejiang province. Ongoing pains in China&#39;s housing market could worsen investor sentiment.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: hector retamal/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The private-sector&#39;s share of China&#39;s 100 largest listed companies by market value dropped from a peak of 55% in mid 2021 to 39% this June, close to its lowest levels in more than three years, according to a forthcoming research report by the Washington, DC-based think tank Peterson Institute for International Economics, or PIIE.</p><p> Private sector investment shrank by 0.2% in the first half of 2023 from a year earlier, the first contraction since official data collection began in 2005, with the exception of 2020, when the economy was racked by the pandemic. In contrast, investment by state-controlled firms expanded 8.1% in the same period.</p><p> Profits at private sector firms, more exposed to falling exports and weak consumer spending, reported a 21% plunge in the first five months of the year. Profits at state-owned enterprises fell 17.7%.</p><p> Ongoing pains in China&#39;s housing market could worsen investor sentiment. Investment by real-estate developers likely accounts for roughly one-third of private investment, according to Tianlei Huang, a research fellow at PIIE.</p><p> The stakes are high for Beijing to rekindle business confidence. A failure to resuscitate the ailing private sector risks pushing Beijing&#39;s full-year growth target of around 5% further out of reach. It may also exacerbate already high youth unemployment.</p><p> For years, private firms, in particular those in the technology, education and property sectors, have absorbed a large share of China&#39;s college graduates.</p><p> Analysts say years of regulatory tightening in those sectors and ongoing distress in the real-estate market have dried up career opportunities for young professionals, helping push China&#39;s youth jobless rate to a record of 21.3% in June.</p><p> In the longer run, the private sector&#39;s retreat would reduce overall efficiency and lead to slower productivity growth, consequences that could ultimately suppress China&#39;s growth potential, economists say.</p><p> Zhang Xuan, a Beijing-based partner of a private-equity firm focusing on technology investment said Beijing&#39;s most recent pledge on supporting the private sector sent a positive message to investors, but hasn&#39;t reassured him about containing a broader economic downturn.</p><p> “The long-term performance of the market can&#39;t simply be governed by a couple policy documents,” he said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Xiao Xiao in Beijing contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Stella Yifan Xie at <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a> and Raffaele Huang at <a href="mailto:raffaele.huang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">raffaele.huang@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 12:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c<author><![CDATA[Stella Yifan XieRaffaele Huang]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> ByteDance</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Rise and Fall of the Chief Diversity Officer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Diversity executives hit the exits as company priorities shift; &#39;everything is a battle&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820139?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> From left: Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive; Dani Monroe, former CDO for Mass General Brigham; and Miriam Warren, CDO for Yelp.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo Illustration: Melinda Starbird, Cheryl Richard, Yelp </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/te-ping-chen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Te-Ping Chen</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lauren Weber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Two years ago chief diversity officers were some of the hottest hires into executive ranks. Now, they increasingly feel left out in the cold.</p><p> Companies including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">Disney</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="company-name">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> have recently said that high-profile diversity, equity and inclusion executives will be leaving their jobs. Thousands of diversity-focused workers have been laid off since last year, and some companies are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scaling back</a> racial justice commitments.</p><p> Diversity, equity and inclusion—or DEI—jobs were put in the crosshairs after many companies started re-examining their executive ranks during the tech sector&#39;s shake out last fall. Some chief diversity officers say their work is facing additional scrutiny since the Supreme Court <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">struck down affirmative action</a> in college admissions and companies brace for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">potential legal challenges</a> . DEI work has also become a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantiss-education-policies-leave-florida-teachers-feeling-unsure-3a81a236?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">political target</a> .</p><p> “There&#39;s a combination of grief, being very tired, and being, in some cases, overwhelmed,” says Miriam Warren, chief diversity officer for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="">Yelp</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> of the challenges facing executives in the field.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In interviews, current and former chief diversity officers said company executives at times didn&#39;t want to change hiring or promotion processes, despite initially telling CDOs they were hired to improve the talent pipeline. The quick about-face shows company enthusiasm for diversity initiatives hasn&#39;t always proved durable, leaving some diversity officers now questioning their career path.</p><p> In the wake of George Floyd&#39;s murder in police custody in May 2020, companies scrambled to hire chief diversity officers, changing the face of the C-suite. In 2018, less than half the companies in the S&amp;P 500 employed someone in the role, and by 2022 three out four companies had created a position, according to a study from Russell Reynolds, an executive search firm.</p><p> Once mostly tasked with HR matters, today&#39;s diversity leaders are expected to weigh in on new product development, marketing efforts and current events that have an impact on how workers and consumers are feeling. Warren and other CDOs said the expanded remit is playing out in a politically divided environment where corporate diversity efforts are the subject of frequent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-new-cause-dodging-the-culture-wars-73e52cf3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">social-media firestorms</a> .</p><h3> Falling demand</h3><p> New analysis from employment data provider Live Data Technologies shows that chief diversity officers have been more vulnerable to layoffs than their human resources counterparts, experiencing 40% higher turnover. Their job searches are also taking longer.</p><p> “I got to 300 applications and then I stopped tracking,” says Stephanie Lubin, who was laid off from her role as diversity head at Drizly, an online alcohol marketplace, in May following the company&#39;s acquisition by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p> In one case, Lubin says she went through 16 rounds of interviews for a role she didn&#39;t get, and says she is now planning to pivot out of DEI work.<p></p><p> The number of CDO searches is down 75% in the past year, says Jason Hanold, chief executive of Hanold Associates Executive Search, which works with Fortune 100 companies to recruit HR and DEI executives, among other roles. Demand is the lowest he has seen in his 30 years of recruiting.</p><p> At the same time, he says, more executives are feeling skittish about taking on diversity roles.</p><p> “They&#39;re telling us, the only way I want to go into another role with DEI is if it includes something else,” he says of the requests for broader titles that offer more responsibilities and resources. He estimates that 60% of diversity roles he is currently filling combine the title with another position, such as chief human resources officer, up from about 10% five years ago.</p><p> During the pandemic, some companies moved people into diversity leadership if they were an ethnic minority, says</p> Dani Monroe, even when they weren&#39;t qualified. Monroe served as CDO for Mass General Brigham, a Boston-based hospital system and one of the largest employers in the state, until 2021 and convenes a yearly gathering of more than 100 CDOs.<p></p><p> “These were knee-jerk reactions,” she says of the hurried CDO hires, adding that some of those elevations didn&#39;t create much impact, leaving both sides feeling disillusioned.</p><h3> On-the-job obstruction</h3><p> American workers are split on the importance of a diverse workforce, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/05/17/diversity-equity-and-inclusion-in-the-workplace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">surveys find</a> .</p><p> Diversity chiefs also encounter obstruction from top executives, says Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive who has worked at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="">AT&amp;T</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> and OfferUp, an online marketplace. Leaders sometimes associate diversity efforts with mandates, such as the equal-employment rules that apply to federal contractors. Those requirements for compliance can create executive resistance that bleeds over into other cultural or policy shifts, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">adding Juneteenth</a> as a company holiday, she says.<p></p><p> “Even if you report to the CEO, it&#39;s still a battle and it&#39;s a smaller budget,” says Starbird, who was laid off from OfferUp in November during a broader restructuring.</p><p> Many diversity executives feel a lack of buy-in from their colleagues. In <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://world50.com/impact?utm_source=wsj&amp;utm_medium=pr&amp;utm_campaign=2023idreport__;!!F0Stn7g!EGLdSj-lMiFGnMwE-GKlWcgVj1tXMu0_-ZbTIyBUUYuQV0JylSZhtrfPiJ-A4c5JWSBx3Po2kxjQHsQPCw$" target="_blank" class="icon none">a survey</a> of 138 diversity executives conducted this spring by World 50 Group, a networking organization for corporate leaders, 82% said they had sufficient influence to do their job, down 6 percentage points from 2022. Asked if they felt supported by middle managers, 41% said yes, an 8-percentage-point drop.</p><p> Since the Supreme Court overturned affirmative action in June, companies are anticipating spillover legal action could have an impact on them. Those that are still hiring CDOs want people who can help the board navigate the political and legal landscape of diversity work and figure out how to take defensive moves to shield them from litigation, says Tina Shah Paikeday, global leader of Russell Reynolds&#39;s diversity, equity and inclusion practice.</p><p> “They recognize it would be smart to get ahead of that.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820155?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, says efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nielsen</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> People are more resistant to company-backed efforts to advance diversity when they are worried about their own jobs, whether because of impending layoffs or disruptions from AI, says David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, the media-ratings company.</p><p> Kenny was both CEO and CDO for a time, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-executive-or-diversity-chief-nielsens-ceo-is-both-11608908446?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking on</a> the diversity role to emphasize how important it was to the future of the business. Even as CEO, it could be a tough sell. Efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p> “A lot of it is, &#39;I&#39;m losing my slice of the pie,&#39; ” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/9d40dc7b-c819-4785-ab9c-4c1e1272d3a7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Te-Ping Chen at <a href="mailto:Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bef2e1de-18c2-41e5-86fb-8b21bfe3c1c7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f<author><![CDATA[Te-Ping ChenLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>Human Resources Consulting</category><category> Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category> Accounting/Consulting</category><category> Business/Consumer Services</category><category> Business Consultancy</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Diversity</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Netflix</category><category> NFLX</category><category>华特迪士尼</category><category>DIS</category><category> AT&amp;T</category><category>时间</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司 A 系列</category><category>世界BD</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace diversity</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>human resources consulting</category><category> broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category> accounting</category><category> consulting</category><category>商业</category><category>consumer services</category><category> business consultancy</category><category> media</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.K. Prime Minister Sunak Suffers Election Setback]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Voters reject Conservatives in two special elections, reflecting anger over inflation, high taxes and creaking public services <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072718"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="589" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821436?width=860&amp;height=589" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Keir Mather of the UK&#39;s opposition Labour Party won Thursday&#39;s special election in the district of Selby and Ainsty.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Danny Lawson/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072718"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/humza-jilani" itemprop="url" rel="author">Humza Jilani</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-colchester" itemprop="url" rel="author">Max Colchester</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 6:37 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-sunak-suffers-election-setback-e4438ee1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> LONDON—The UK&#39;s ruling Conservative Party lost special elections in two of its strongholds as voters expressed anger with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-s-stubborn-inflation-means-more-pain-for-homeowners-renters-94f44e96?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">stagnant British economy</a> and high inflation, pointing to the challenges Prime Minister Rishi Sunak could face in a general election next year.</p><p> The loss in Selby and Ainsty—a district with deep Conservative roots—reflects discontent in a country where <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nhs-uk-national-health-service-strike-costs-11675693883?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">public services are creaking</a> , taxes are at a 70-year high and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-england-interest-rates-fb6332a6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mortgage costs</a> are rising sharply. In Somerton and Frome, a southwestern district, the centrist Liberal Democrats took a seat that the Conservatives had last won by 29 points.</p><p> National opinion polls show the opposition Labour Party with a 22-point lead over the Conservative Party, according to Ipsos.</p><p> The special elections held Thursday also expose the cracks in the Conservatives&#39; disparate, post-Brexit electoral coalition. In 2019, the Conservatives <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/britain-votes-in-an-election-that-will-set-the-course-of-brexit-11576156488?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">won a big majority</a> by uniting a coalition of blue-collar, Brexit-friendly and immigration-skeptical former Labour voters in the north of England with the more traditional, wealthy Conservatives in the south. The latest results show this voter base splitting apart.</p><p> The three special elections were held to replace three Conservative lawmakers who quit Parliament, including former Prime Minister <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/boris-johnson">Boris Johnson</a> , who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-british-leader-boris-johnson-quits-as-lawmaker-ahead-of-partygate-report-767a4baa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">resigned in protest</a> against a parliamentary report that found he had intentionally lied to lawmakers about his attendance at parties during Covid-19. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819965?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak said this week&#39;s results show the next general election isn&#39;t &#39;a done deal.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: UK PARLIAMENT/JESSICA TAYLOR/via REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The biggest setback came in Selby, in northern England, where Labour flipped a seat that had consistently voted for the Conservatives since World War II. The Conservatives had won it by 35 points in 2019.</p><p> “It is clear just how powerful the demand for change is,” Keir Starmer, the Labour Party&#39;s leader, said after the results. Sunak cautioned that the outcome shows that the general election, which will likely be held in fall next year, isn&#39;t “a done deal.”</p><p> A reprieve for Sunak came in Uxbridge, a West London district formerly held by Johnson. The Conservatives held on to the seat by just 495 votes, defying expectations that they would lose the ballot. Local outrage over a planned expansion of a pollution tax on older vehicles entering the district provided enough of a bounce to allow Conservatives to cling to power there.</p><p> Thursday&#39;s losses highlight Sunak&#39;s struggle to deliver on his pledges to fix Britain&#39;s strike-ridden nationalized healthcare service, contain illegal migration and tame inflation that is running at the highest rate in the Group of Seven nations.</p><p> Sunak, a former Goldman Sachs banker, has marketed himself as a technocrat who can tackle these ills and steer his party to a record fifth consecutive term in office in a general election that must take place by early 2025. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8721652E-C4D0-4BCA-A94F-5BE086258F7E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-k-prime-minister-sunak-suffers-election-setback-e4438ee1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Core inflation is rising in the UK while falling in other big economies like the US WSJ&#39;s Anna Hirtenstein explains why, and how it affects Prime Minister Rishi Sunak&#39;s goal of halving inflation by the end of 2023. Illustration: Daniel Orton/WSJ<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>But time is running out. “Today, the Conservatives don&#39;t have credibility on the economy, and Rishi doesn&#39;t have long to resolve that” before next year&#39;s election, said Robert Hayward, a pollster and Conservative Party member of the House of Lords.</p><p> The UK&#39;s high inflation is a result of a tight job market putting upward pressure on wages and the lingering food and energy price spikes from Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine in early 2022.</p><p> However, data published Wednesday showed that inflation for June fell to a 15-month low of 7.9%, a larger-than-expected fall and an encouraging sign for the government&#39;s promise to bring inflation down to 5% by the end of the year. Officials close to Sunak say the data suggested that real wages could be rising by the time an election is called. That might enable the Conservatives to deliver a pre-election tax cut in an effort to jolt the UK out of its stagnant growth rate.</p><p> But inflation isn&#39;t the government&#39;s only political headache. Public services are suffering from years of underfunding, overcrowding and a wave of worker strikes in recent years. The waiting list for treatment by the National Health Service has ballooned to more than seven million people. Striking workers have forced school closures and public-transportation cancellations.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Can Prime Minister Rishi Sunak turn his party around before the next general election?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Meanwhile, Sunak has pledged to halt the flow of migrant boats crossing the English Channel. So far this year, nearly 14,000 migrants have used dinghies to sail across from France to British shores, slightly fewer than the 15,280 who crossed during the same period last year.</p><p> All three elections Thursday were in districts where a majority of constituents had voted to leave the European Union in 2016—a position advocated by the Conservatives. But swaths of voters still turned decisively against the party that has staked its political identity on delivering the promised fruits of Brexit.</p><p> John Hensley, who served as a local mayor in the Uxbridge constituency from 2016 to 2017, voted against the Conservative Party for the first time in his life.</p><p> Like the majority of Uxbridge constituents, he also voted to leave the EU in 2016, persuaded by claims that Brexit would free up hundreds of millions of pounds to spend on the NHS and other essential services.</p><p> But his monthslong wait to see a doctor, growing grocery bills and frustration with government scandals have soured him on his lifelong party and on Brexit.</p><p> “My vote is a signal to the government that we can&#39;t keep going on like this,” he said.</p><p> Write to Humza Jilani at <a href="mailto:humza.jilani@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">humza.jilani@wsj.com</a> and Max Colchester at <a href="mailto:Max.Colchester@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Max.Colchester@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 10:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-prime-minister-sunak-suffers-election-setback-e4438ee1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-prime-minister-sunak-suffers-election-setback-e4438ee1<author><![CDATA[Humza JilaniMax Colchester]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Government Finance</category><category> Government Budget/Taxation</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>里希·苏纳克</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>government finance</category><category> government budget</category><category> taxation</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Untangling the U.S. From China’s Economy Is Messy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Janet Yellen&#39;s &#39;friendshoring&#39; push is complicated by crisscrossing supply chains <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071011"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819897?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen visited Beijing this month as part of a US effort to stabilize relations.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: THOMAS PETER/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071011"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andrew-duehren" itemprop="url" rel="author">Andrew Duehren</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/untangling-the-u-s-from-chinas-economy-is-messy-8a658f2e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HANOI, Vietnam—The Biden administration&#39;s attempt to surgically cut economic ties with China is proving difficult to execute.</p><p> Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen visited Vietnam this week to discuss her push for “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-calls-for-friend-shoring-trade-to-diversify-from-china-11658200959?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">friendshoring</a> ,” a term she uses to call for companies to shift supply chains from China to friendlier nations. Trade between the US and Vietnam has exploded in the last five years, reaching roughly $140 billion in 2022 from $60 billion in 2018.</p><p> “We see great potential going forward to deepen those relationships,” Yellen said while touring a Hanoi factory that relies on some Chinese components. She repeatedly praised the growing ties in meetings with Vietnamese Prime Minister Pham Minh Chinh and other Communist Party officials during her visit.</p><p> Disentangling China&#39;s role in global supply chains, even in limited areas, is far from straightforward. The share of US goods imports from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-imported-more-cars-phones-supplies-from-abroad-9157aca6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">China slipped</a> in recent years, while it expanded with other Asian countries. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EA224A41-9ED5-4FFE-94DD-F6BDB9AE59AB&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Funtangling-the-u-s-from-chinas-economy-is-messy-8a658f2e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen concluded a visit to China on Sunday by saying both sides are making progress on managing economic and national-security tensions. She added that a decoupling of the world&#39;s two largest economies is “impossible.” Photo: Mark R. Cristino/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Many of those alternative trading partners such as Vietnam or South Korea are themselves deeply intertwined with China. China&#39;s dominance in clean energy technology makes the Biden administration hesitant to push companies to completely avoid Chinese products. And precisely identifying the industries where the US and its allies see China posing a threat is challenging.</p><p> Earlier this month, Yellen <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-says-u-s-doesnt-seek-winner-take-all-fight-with-china-72ab3c95?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">told her Chinese counterparts</a> in Beijing that the US goal is to reduce exposure to China in key sectors without jeopardizing trade and investment flows that benefit both countries.</p><h3> Friendly partners retain close ties to China</h3><p> Vietnamese production in many cases still involves Chinese companies.</p><p> In Hanoi, Yellen toured a factory for Selex Motors, which produces electric motorcycles. The company uses Chinese suppliers for electric motors and some electronic connectors, switches and shock absorbers, according to the company&#39;s chief executive. He said 80% of the company&#39;s supplies are sourced locally.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should the US continue to seek economic decoupling with China? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Vietnam has become an important provider of solar panels to the US</p><p> A Commerce Department probe, though, found that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-solar-manufacturers-dodged-u-s-tariffs-probe-finds-11669952820?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chinese companies circumvented tariffs</a> by rerouting their products through Vietnam and three other southeast Asian countries.</p><p> The finding would have subjected solar panels from Vietnam and those other nations to significantly higher tariffs, but the Biden administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-to-waive-solar-import-tariffs-for-two-years-11654525408?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">deferred the levies</a> amid concerns about solar-panel costs rising in the US</p><p> A senior Treasury official said that Chinese companies aren&#39;t involved in much of the increase of trade between the US and Vietnam, pointing to favorable economic conditions in Vietnam that have driven growth.</p><p> New American subsidies <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-ev-rules-mean-fewer-models-eligible-for-tax-credit-98b6b63c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to help consumers purchase electric vehicles</a> , which aim to reduce dependence on China while cutting carbon emissions, face a similar challenge. To be eligible for the subsidy, a vehicle&#39;s battery must be largely built from components and minerals that come from the US or one of its free-trade partners. China isn&#39;t such a partner. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820752?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Biden toured a Samsung semiconductor plant in South Korea last year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: JONATHAN ERNST/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> US has yet to define which firms are a concern</h3><p> A coming rule will take the requirements a step further by barring from qualification batteries that include any materials from a “foreign entity of concern.”</p><p> Whether the Biden administration broadly defines a “foreign entity of concern” to include many Chinese suppliers, or more narrowly targets it to only certain firms, will carry huge consequences for the availability of the credit. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-controls-minerals-that-run-the-worldand-just-fired-a-warning-shot-at-u-s-5961d77b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chinese companies dominate</a> the manufacture of battery components and the supply of the minerals in them. Completely removing Chinese products from the supply chain could prove impossible for automakers in the near future. Some US companies have even <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-invests-3-5-billion-in-michigan-battery-plant-with-chinese-partners-technology-1aed174c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">planned to join with Chinese firms</a> on battery production.</p><p> In an interview, Yellen said defining a “foreign entity of concern” was “quite complicated,” adding that Treasury&#39;s rules would stay within the bounds of the Inflation Reduction Act.</p><p> “But in places that there is some scope, we certainly keep in mind that we don&#39;t want to make it impossible—to be so focused on supply-chain resilience that we don&#39;t meet any of our objectives about getting cars on the road,” Yellen said.</p><p> With other clean-energy subsidies, the Biden administration has written rules that take a looser view of sourcing requirements than some US manufacturers had hoped, clearing the way to use Chinese supplies in subsidized clean-energy construction. The Biden administration has also <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-allow-south-korean-taiwan-chip-makers-to-keep-operations-in-china-5d7d72cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">allowed top semiconductor manufacturers</a> in South Korea and Taiwan to keep selling into China despite US export controls.</p><p> The Biden administration is also crafting new rules for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-grapples-with-potential-threats-from-chinese-ai-7d1f2e70?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">restricting some US investment into China</a> , but it is still sorting through how the rules will apply to foreign subsidiaries of US firms, among other details. The restrictions will apply to US private-equity and venture-capital investments in semiconductors, quantum computing and artificial intelligence, prohibiting some investments in those sectors while requiring disclosure of others.</p><p> The goal of the order is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-prepares-new-rules-on-investment-in-technology-abroad-a451e035?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to prevent American investors</a> from helping Chinese companies develop technology that could be used against the US or its allies in a military confrontation.</p><p> “It hasn&#39;t been finally decided so I don&#39;t want to say it&#39;s going to happen, but I believe it will happen and I think this summer is most likely,” Yellen said in an interview, referring to the new investment rules.</p><p> The US is encouraging its allies in Europe to take similar steps to protect supply chains and limit Beijing&#39;s access to Western expertise. Finding the right balance is proving difficult for them, too.</p><p> “We need to trade with China, and at the same time we need to make critical strategic supply chains more secure,” Paolo Gentiloni, the European Commissioner for the Economy, said in an interview. “Easy in words, but not obvious in practical terms.”</p><p> Write to Andrew Duehren at <a href="mailto:andrew.duehren@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrew.duehren@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/untangling-the-us-from-chinas-economy-is-messy-8a658f2e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/untangling-the-us-from-chinas-economy-is-messy-8a658f2e<author><![CDATA[Andrew Duehren]]></author><category> Electrical Components/Equipment</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Supply Chain</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Janet Yellen</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>supply chain</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>electrical components</category><category> equipment</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Rise as Energy Export Powerhouse Hinges on One Town]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pipelines to Corpus Christi, Texas, are near capacity as US oil production approaches records <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821191/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="2023 年上半年，除了精炼燃料外，每日约有 200 万桶原油出口通过德克萨斯州科珀斯克里斯蒂市。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> About 2 million barrels of daily crude exports passed through Corpus Christi, Texas, in the first half of 2023, in addition to refined fuels. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071302"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071302"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-uberti" itemprop="url" rel="author">David Uberti</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-morenne" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoît Morenne</a></span> | Photographs by Verónica G. Cárdenas for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The US has transformed global markets by boosting crude-oil exports more than 30-fold over the past decade. Much of the boom hinges on Corpus Christi Bay.</p><p> In the first four months of 2023, about half of the country&#39;s 4.1 million barrels of daily shipments abroad was loaded onto skyscraper-size tankers from this stretch of Texas coastline, destined to become fuel for overseas travelers or factories. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821234?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> That <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-oil-boom-blunts-opecs-pricing-power-472567f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">gusher of supply</a> has helped blunt the increase in prices from recent production cuts by Saudi Arabia and Russia. In Europe, oil and natural gas shipped from the Gulf Coast <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-regains-its-energy-clout-as-ukraine-war-enters-second-year-2b910ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have backstopped the continent</a> as it weaned itself off Russian energy after the outbreak of the war on Ukraine.</p><p> Corpus Christi has become the dominant US hub, siphoning crude from elsewhere thanks to unique terminals that make it cheaper than competitors. Now, ballooning trade from the port has put the US on pace to pump out record oil exports this year, according to federal record-keepers.</p><p> But with pipelines nearing capacity and US output set to reach new heights, competition is heating up among companies and investors over how to connect the American oil patch to a fuel-hungry world.</p><p> “The market is totally focused on taking shale production from the US into international markets,” said Rusty Braziel, chief executive of consulting firm RBN Energy.</p><p> Corpus Christi is the closest deep-draft port to the Permian Basin in West Texas and New Mexico, America&#39;s hottest oil field. Crude extracted from shale rock there, prized by overseas refineries for its light, sweet quality, trades at a premium to many other grades. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a3d36427-a351-47de-864b-cce33645a7a6.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> That oil was confined stateside as the shale boom unleashed unprecedented US production growth. But after Washington nixed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-leaders-agree-to-lift-40-year-ban-on-oil-exports-1450242995?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">decades-old export restrictions</a> in 2015, companies scrambled to build out pipelines to Corpus Christi, a South Texas city of about 320,000.</p><p> Various companies have since constructed storage tanks in Corpus Christi to hold tens of millions more barrels of oil near the water. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LNG" class="company-name">Cheniere Energy</a></p> is expanding a plant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-fracked-gas-ukraine-invasion-europe-import-9e5cc725?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">that can liquefy natural gas</a> for export. Since 2020, dredgers have been at work deepening the port&#39;s ship channel and inner harbor to 54 feet from 47 feet currently, a more than $680 million operation that will allow many tankers to fill up close to capacity.<p></p><p> “You can&#39;t just build those facilities overnight,” said Kent Britton, the Port of Corpus Christi&#39;s interim chief executive. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821161?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Ensuing growth in crude shipments has outpaced other launch points in Texas and Louisiana largely because of the economics of shipping. Exporters that operate from Houston-Galveston and the main Port of Corpus Christi funnel shipments to smaller classes of tankers, which either carry cargoes abroad or ferry them to 1,100-foot supertankers anchored offshore in a dayslong process.</p><p> But across Corpus Christi Bay, in the small town of Ingleside, Texas, oil terminals at a former Naval base are big enough that those massive ships can fill up about half of their 2 million barrels of capacity from shore.</p><p> “You can pretty much load your million barrels in 24 hours,” said Lois Zabrocky, chief executive of</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/INSW" class="">International Seaways</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which operates 13 so-called very large crude carriers.<p></p><p> Five tugboats then guide half-full VLCCs several miles out to sea, where smaller tankers top them off for delivery to refineries in Europe, Asia or elsewhere. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821156?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> That streamlined loading process can pare the price of shipments compared with elsewhere on the Gulf Coast. Analysts said such differences became particularly crucial last year after Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine whipsawed energy markets and sent shipping costs skyrocketing.</p><p> Calgary, Alberta-based <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CA/XTSE/GEI" class="company-name">Gibson Energy</a> bought one of the Ingleside terminals in June for $1.1 billion, an investment that Chief Executive</p> Steven Spaulding said will pay off regardless of whether Permian production growth continues. His rationale: Ingleside&#39;s efficiency will entice traders, even if it means drawing oil away from across Corpus Christi Bay.<p></p><p> “It doesn&#39;t matter to our terminal,” Spaulding said.</p><p> Pipelines from the Permian to Corpus Christi are running at about 90% capacity, according to East Daley Analytics, a level at which traders might begin sending more crude toward Houston for refining or shipment abroad.</p><p> The midstream energy company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ENB" class="company-name">Enbridge</a> has responded by announcing an expansion of its pipeline to Corpus Christi by 200,000 barrels a day. Other companies have proposed environmentally contentious plans for multibillion-dollar deepwater terminals that would allow VLCCs to load up fully in the Gulf of Mexico. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821198?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A liquid terminal in Ingleside, Texas, a port with capacity to accommodate supertankers.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For all their customers&#39; focus on oil-and-gas exports, Corpus officials are preparing for a future when the US exports nonfossil-fuel commodities such as hydrogen and ammonia. The port authority applied to receive some of the $8 billion that Washington pledged in its 2021 infrastructure package to develop regional hubs aimed at accelerating the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-name-investors-pour-billions-into-clean-hydrogen-projects-11657792800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">use of hydrogen for energy</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What are the implications of Texas&#39; growing prominence in the global energy trade?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Enbridge has said it would partner with the Norwegian fertilizer company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YARIY" class="company-name">Yara International</a> to develop a plant to produce up to 1.4 million tons of ammonia a year at its Ingleside terminal. The companies plan to capture <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carbon-capture-projects-are-taking-off-heres-how-they-stash-the-greenhouse-gas-11666928082?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">carbon dioxide</a> produced during the process and store it underground—activity that could qualify for credits under President Biden&#39;s climate law.</p><p> Corpus Christi “is hopefully the gift that&#39;s going to keep on giving,” said Phil Anderson, senior vice president, business development, at Enbridge.</p><p> Write to David Uberti at <a href="mailto:david.uberti@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.uberti@wsj.com</a> and Benoît Morenne at <a href="mailto:benoit.morenne@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.morenne@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c<author><![CDATA[David UbertiBenoît Morenne]]></author><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>Energy</category><category> Oil and Gas Upstream Operations</category><category> Oil extraction</category><category> Oil and Natural Gas Exploration</category><category> Fossil Fuels</category><category> Oil and Gas</category><category>油</category><category>Capacity/Facilities</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> capacity</category><category> facilities</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>energy</category><category> oil and gas upstream operations</category><category> oil extraction</category><category> oil and natural gas exploration</category><category> fossil fuels</category><category> oil and gas</category><category> oil</category></item></channel></rss>